<?php $__env->startSection('content'); ?><p>Four new cases of COVID-19 have been diagnosed in New South Wales on Friday as thousands of school children break for holidays.</p>

<p>Three cases are returned travellers who are in hotel quarantine, while another the fourth is someone who was at a Woolworths in Campbelltown Mall, western Sydney.</p>

<p>Anyone who was at the supermarket in the shopping centre between 1.30pm and 2pm on September 17 is considered a casual contact and must monitor for symptoms. </p>

<p>The man in his 50s, who's case was announced on Thursday, has not come into contact with a known case. </p>

<p>Contact tracing and investigations continue. </p>

<p>Testing numbers have dropped over recent weeks and health authorities urge people, particular in South Western Sydney, to come forward and get tested if they have symptoms.  </p>

<p>More to come.  </p>
